{"title_page": "Map (mathematics)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|map (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Function_color_example_3.svg|thumb|One type of map is a function, as in the association of any of the four colored shapes in X to its color in Y.]]\nIn [[mathematics]], the term '''mapping''', sometimes shortened as '''map''', is a general function between two mathematical objects or structures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mathvault.ca/math-glossary/#map|title=The Definitive Glossary of Higher Mathematical Jargon \u2014 Mapping|last=|first=|date=2019-08-01|website=Math Vault|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://mathworld.wolfram.com/Map.html|title=Map|last=Weisstein|first=Eric W.|website=mathworld.wolfram.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> It can be thought of as the mathematical abstraction of the process of making a geographical map.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/science/mapping|title=Mapping {{!}} mathematics|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\nMaps may either be ''functions'' or ''morphisms'', though the terms share some overlap.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>The words '''map''', '''mapping''', '''transformation''', '''correspondence''', and '''operator''' are often used synonymously. {{harvnb|Halmos|1970|p=30}}. In many authors, the term 'map' is with a more general meaning than 'function', which may be restricted to having domains of sets of numbers only. </ref> In the sense of a [[function (mathematics)|function]], a map is often associated with some sort of structure, particularly a set constituting the [[codomain]].<ref>{{cite book |first=T. M. |last=Apostol |authorlink=Tom M. Apostol |title=Mathematical Analysis |year=1981 |publisher=Addison-Wesley |isbn=0-201-00288-4 |page=35 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.toronto.edu/~stacho/macm101-2.pdf|title=Function, one-to-one, onto|last=Stacho|first=Juraj|date=October 31, 2007|website=cs.toronto.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> Alternatively, a map may be described by a [[morphism]] in category theory, which generalizes the idea of a function. In some occasions, the term \"[[Transformation (function)|transformation]]\" can also be used interchangeably.<ref name=\":1\" /> There are also a few less common uses in [[logic]] and [[graph theory]]. \n\n==Maps as functions==\n{{Main article|Function (mathematics)}}\n\nIn many branches of mathematics, the term '''map''' is used to mean a [[Function (mathematics)|function]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.math-only-math.com/functions-or-mapping.html|title=Functions or Mapping {{!}} Learning Mapping {{!}} Function as a Special Kind of Relation|website=Math Only Math|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/education/news-wires-white-papers-and-books/mapping-mathematical|title=Mapping, Mathematical {{!}} Encyclopedia.com|website=www.encyclopedia.com|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> sometimes with a specific property of particular importance to that branch. For instance, a \"map\" is a ''[[continuous function]]'' in [[topology]], a ''[[Linear map|linear transformation]]'' in [[linear algebra]], etc.\n\nSome authors, such as [[Serge Lang]],<ref>{{cite book |first=Serge |last=Lang |title=Linear Algebra |edition=2nd |year=1971 |page=83 |publisher=Addison-Wesley |isbn=0-201-04211-8 }}</ref> use \"function\" only to refer to maps in which the [[codomain]] is a set of numbers (i.e. a subset of [[real numbers|'''R''']] or [[complex numbers|'''C''']]), and reserve the term \"mapping\" for more general functions.\n\nMaps of certain kinds are the subjects of many important theories. These include [[Homomorphism|homomorphisms]] in [[abstract algebra]], [[Isometry|isometries]] in [[geometry]], [[Operation (mathematics)|operators]] in [[Mathematical analysis|analysis]] and [[Group representation|representations]] in [[group theory]].<ref name=\":1\" />  For more, see [[Lie group]], [[mapping class group]] and [[permutation group]].<!-- many more to add here-->\n\nIn the theory of [[dynamical system]]s, a map denotes an [[Discrete-time dynamical system|evolution function]] used to create [[Dynamical system#Maps|discrete dynamical systems]]. See [[Poincar\u00e9 map]] for more.\n\nA ''partial map'' is a ''[[partial function]]'', and a ''total map'' is a ''[[total function]]''. Related terms such as ''[[Domain (mathematics)|domain]]'', ''[[codomain]]'', ''[[Injective function|injective]]'', ''[[Continuous function|continuous]]'', etc. can be applied equally to maps and functions, with the same meaning. All these usages can be applied to \"maps\" as general functions or as functions with special properties.\n\n==Maps as morphisms==\n{{Main article|Morphism}}\n\nIn [[category theory]], \"map\" is often used as a synonym for \"[[morphism]]\" or \"arrow\", and thus is more general than \"function\".<ref>{{cite book |title=An Introduction to Category Theory |first=H. |last=Simmons |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2011 |isbn=978-1-139-50332-7 |page=2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VOCQUC_uiWgC&pg=PA2 }}</ref> For example, a morphism <math>f:\\, X \\to Y</math> in a [[concrete category]] (i.e. a morphism which can be viewed as functions) carries with it the information of its domain (the source <math>X</math> of the morphism) and its codomain (the target <math>Y</math>). In the widely used definition of a function <math>f:X\\to Y</math>, <math>f</math> is a subset of <math>X\\times Y</math> consisting of all the pairs <math>(x,f(x))</math> for <math>x\\in X</math>. In this sense, the function doesn't capture the information of which set <math>Y</math> is used as the codomain; only the range <math>f(X)</math> is determined by the function.\n\n==Other uses==\n===In logic===\nIn [[formal logic]], the term '''map''' is sometimes used for a ''[[functional predicate]]'', whereas a function is a [[model (logic)|model]] of such a [[Predicate (logic)|predicate]] in [[set theory]].\n\n===In graph theory===\n[[File:Dodecahedron schlegel diagram.png|thumb|An example of a map in [[graph theory]]]]\n\nIn [[graph theory]], a '''map''' is a drawing of a [[Graph (discrete mathematics)|graph]] on a surface without overlapping edges (an [[Graph embedding|embedding]]). If the surface is a [[Plane (geometry)|plane]] then a map is a [[planar graph]], similar to a [[political map]].<ref>{{cite book |first1=Jonathan |last1=Gross |first2=Jay |last2=Yellen |title=Graph Theory and its applications |year=1998 |publisher=CRC Press |isbn=0-8493-3982-0 |page=294 }}</ref>\n\n===In computer science===\nIn the communities surrounding [[programming language]]s that treat functions as [[first-class citizen]]s, a [[Map (higher-order function)|map]] is often referred to as the [[Binary function|binary]] [[higher-order function]] that takes a function ''f'' and a [[List (abstract data type)|list]] {{nowrap|[''v''<sub>0</sub>, ''v''<sub>1</sub>, ..., ''v''<sub>''n''</sub>]}} as [[Argument of a function|arguments]] and returns {{nowrap|[''f''(''v''<sub>0</sub>), ''f''(''v''<sub>1</sub>), ..., ''f''(''v''<sub>''n''</sub>)]}} (where {{nowrap|''n'' \u2265 0}}).\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Apply|Apply function]]\n* [[Bijection, injection and surjection]]\n* [[Category theory]]\n* [[Homeomorphism]]\n* [[Homomorphism]]\n* [[List of chaotic maps]]\n* [[Mapping class group]]\n* [[Projection (mathematics)]]\n* [[Regular map (algebraic geometry)]]\n* [[Regular map (graph theory)]]\n* [[Topology]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Mathematical logic}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Functions and mappings| ]]\n[[Category:Basic concepts in set theory]]\n[[pt:Mapa (matem\u00e1tica)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|map (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Function_color_example_3.svg|thumb|One type of map is a function, as in the association of any of the four colored shapes in X to its color in Y.]]\nIn [[mathematics]], the term '''mapping''', sometimes shortened as '''map''', is a general function between two mathematical objects or structures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mathvault.ca/math-glossary/#map|title=The Definitive Glossary of Higher Mathematical Jargon \u2014 Mapping|last=|first=|date=2019-08-01|website=Math Vault|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://mathworld.wolfram.com/Map.html|title=Map|last=Weisstein|first=Eric W.|website=mathworld.wolfram.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> It can be thought of as the mathematical abstraction of the process of making a geographical map.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/science/mapping|title=Mapping {{!}} mathematics|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\nMaps may either be ''functions'' or ''morphisms'', though the terms share some overlap.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>The words '''map''', '''mapping''', '''transformation''', '''correspondence''', and '''operator''' are often used synonymously. {{harvnb|Halmos|1970|p=30}}. In many authors, the term 'map' is with a more general meaning than 'function', which may be restricted to having domains of sets of numbers only. </ref> In the sense of a [[function (mathematics)|function]], a map is often associated with some sort of structure, particularly a set constituting the [[codomain]].<ref>{{cite book |first=T. M. |last=Apostol |authorlink=Tom M. Apostol |title=Mathematical Analysis |year=1981 |publisher=Addison-Wesley |isbn=0-201-00288-4 |page=35 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.toronto.edu/~stacho/macm101-2.pdf|title=Function, one-to-one, onto|last=Stacho|first=Juraj|date=October 31, 2007|website=cs.toronto.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> Alternatively, a map may be described by a [[morphism]] in category theory, which generalizes the idea of a function. In some occasions, the term \"[[Transformation (function)|transformation]]\" can also be used interchangeably.<ref name=\":1\" /> There are also a few less common uses in [[logic]] and [[graph theory]]. \n\n==Maps as functions==\n{{Main article|Function (mathematics)}}\n\nIn many branches of mathematics, the term '''map''' is used to mean a [[Function (mathematics)|function]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.math-only-math.com/functions-or-mapping.html|title=Functions or Mapping {{!}} Learning Mapping {{!}} Function as a Special Kind of Relation|website=Math Only Math|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/education/news-wires-white-papers-and-books/mapping-mathematical|title=Mapping, Mathematical {{!}} Encyclopedia.com|website=www.encyclopedia.com|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> sometimes with a specific property of particular importance to that branch. For instance, a \"map\" is a ''[[continuous function]]'' in [[topology]], a ''[[Linear map|linear transformation]]'' in [[linear algebra]], etc.\n\nSome authors, such as [[Serge Lang]],<ref>{{cite book |first=Serge |last=Lang |title=Linear Algebra |edition=2nd |year=1971 |page=83 |publisher=Addison-Wesley |isbn=0-201-04211-8 }}</ref> use \"function\" only to refer to maps in which the [[codomain]] is a set of numbers (i.e. a subset of [[real numbers|'''R''']] or [[complex numbers|'''C''']]), and reserve the term \"mapping\" for more general functions.\n\nMaps of certain kinds are the subjects of many important theories. These include [[Homomorphism|homomorphisms]] in [[abstract algebra]], [[Isometry|isometries]] in [[geometry]], [[Operation (mathematics)|operators]] in [[Mathematical analysis|analysis]] and [[Group representation|representations]] in [[group theory]].<ref name=\":1\" />  For more, see [[Lie group]], [[mapping class group]] and [[permutation group]].<!-- many more to add here-->\n\nIn the theory of [[dynamical system]]s, a map denotes an [[Discrete-time dynamical system|evolution function]] used to create [[Dynamical system#Maps|discrete dynamical systems]]. See [[Poincar\u00e9 map]] for more.\n\nA ''partial map'' is a ''[[partial function]]'', and a ''total map'' is a ''[[total function]]''. Related terms such as ''[[Domain (mathematics)|domain]]'', ''[[codomain]]'', ''[[Injective function|injective]]'', ''[[Continuous function|continuous]]'', etc. can be applied equally to maps and functions, with the same meaning. All these usages can be applied to \"maps\" as general functions or as functions with special properties.\n\n==Maps as morphisms==\n{{Main article|Morphism}}\n\nIn [[category theory]], \"map\" is often used as a synonym for \"[[morphism]]\" or \"arrow\", and thus is more general than \"function\".<ref>{{cite book |title=An Introduction to Category Theory |first=H. |last=Simmons |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2011 |isbn=978-1-139-50332-7 |page=2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VOCQUC_uiWgC&pg=PA2 }}</ref> For example, a morphism <math>f:\\, X \\to Y</math> in a [[concrete category]] (i.e. a morphism which can be viewed as functions) carries with it the information of its domain (the source <math>X</math> of the morphism) and its codomain (the target <math>Y</math>). In the widely used definition of a function <math>f:X\\to Y</math>, <math>f</math> is a subset of <math>X\\times Y</math> consisting of all the pairs <math>(x,f(x))</math> for <math>x\\in X</math>. In this sense, the function doesn't capture the information of which set <math>Y</math> is used as the codomain; only the range <math>f(X)</math> is determined by the function.\n\n==Other uses==\n===In logic===\nIn [[formal logic]], the term '''map''' is sometimes used for a ''[[functional predicate]]'', whereas a function is a [[model (logic)|model]] of such a [[Predicate (logic)|predicate]] in [[set theory]].\n\n===In graph theory===\n[[File:Dodecahedron schlegel diagram.png|thumb|An example of a map in [[graph theory]]]]\n\nIn [[graph theory]], a '''map''' is a drawing of a [[Graph (discrete mathematics)|graph]] on a surface without overlapping edges (an [[Graph embedding|embedding]]). If the surface is a [[Plane (geometry)|plane]] then a map is a [[planar graph]], similar to a [[political map]].<ref>{{cite book |first1=Jonathan |last1=Gross |first2=Jay |last2=Yellen |title=Graph Theory and its applications |year=1998 |publisher=CRC Press |isbn=0-8493-3982-0 |page=294 }}</ref>\n\n===In computer science===\nIn the communities surrounding [[programming language]]s that treat functions as [[first-class citizen]]s, a [[Map (higher-order function)|map]] is often referred to as the [[Binary function|binary]] [[higher-order function]] that takes a function ''f'' and a [[List (abstract data type)|list]] {{nowrap|[''v''<sub>0</sub>, ''v''<sub>1</sub>, ..., ''v''<sub>''n''</sub>]}} as [[Argument of a function|arguments]] and returns {{nowrap|[''f''(''v''<sub>0</sub>), ''f''(''v''<sub>1</sub>), ..., ''f''(''v''<sub>''n''</sub>)]}} (where {{nowrap|''n'' \u2265 0}}).\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Apply|Apply function]]\n* [[Bijection, injection and surjection]]\n* [[Category theory]]\n* [[Homeomorphism]]\n* [[Homomorphism]]\n* [[List of chaotic maps]]\n* [[Mapping class group]]\n* [[Projection (mathematics)]]\n* [[Regular map (algebraic geometry)]]\n* [[Regular map (graph theory)]]\n* [[Topology]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Mathematical logic}}\n\n[[Category:Functions and mappings| ]]\n[[Category:Basic concepts in set theory]]\n[[pt:Mapa (matem\u00e1tica)]]\n", "name_user": "MathXplore", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Map_(mathematics)"}
{"title_page": "People's Liberation Army Special Operations Forces", "text_new": "{{short description|Chinese Special Operations Forces}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name = People's Liberation Army Special Operations Forces\n|native_name= \u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u6c11\u89e3\u653e\u519b\u7279\u79cd\u90e8\u961f\n|image = Pla ensign sof.jpg\n|image_size = 200\n|caption = An example of PLA Special Operations Forces insignia\n|dates = 1988 \u2013 Present\n|allegiance = [[File:Flag_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party.svg|23px]] [[Communist Party of China]]\n|country = {{Flag|People's Republic of China}}\n|branch = {{Flagicon image|Ground Force Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|size=23px}} [[People's Liberation Army Ground Force]]<br />{{Flagicon image|Naval Ensign of the People's Republic of China.svg|size=23px}} [[People's Liberation Army Navy]]<br />{{Flagicon image|Air Force Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|size=23px}} [[People's Liberation Army Air Force]]<br />{{Flagicon image|Rocket Force Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|size=23px}} [[People's Liberation Army Rocket Force]]\n|type = [[Special forces]]\n|command_structure =\n|role = [[Special operations]]<br />[[Counter-terrorism]]<br />[[Military intelligence]]<br />(Deployable & operational from land, air and sea)\n|size= [[Classified information|Classified]]; Analysts believe current size is between 7,000 and 14,000 troops.{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n|current_commander =\n|garrison =\n|ceremonial_chief =\n|ceremonial_chief_label =\n|colonel_of_the_regiment = \n|nickname =\n|motto =\n|colors =\n|march =\n|mascot =\n|battles= [[Piracy in Somalia|Counter-piracy operations]]\n|notable_commanders =\n|anniversaries =\n}}\n\nThe '''People's Liberation Army special operations forces''' ({{zh\n|s = \u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u6c11\u89e3\u653e\u519b\u7279\u79cd\u90e8\u961f\n|t = \u4e2d\u570b\u4eba\u6c11\u89e3\u653e\u8ecd\u7279\u7a2e\u90e8\u968a\n|p = Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 R\u00e9nm\u00edn Ji\u011bf\u00e0ngj\u016bn t\u00e8zh\u01d2ng b\u00f9du\u00ec }}) are the [[special forces]] of the [[People's Republic of China|Chinese]] [[People's Liberation Army]] (PLA). The size of the Special Operations Forces is estimated to be between 7,000 and 14,000 troops. The forces intended combat role is as rapid-response units in the event of a limited regional war under high-tech conditions. They also carry out commando, counter-terrorism, and intelligence gathering operations. \n\nThe building up of China's special forces represents a shift in the country's operational thinking, from an army-dominated force structure to emphasizing integrated joint operations, with a flexible elite force.\n\n== History ==\nThe PLA's interest in modern special warfare was first noted in the mid-1980s when it was shifting its military stance from a \"[[people's war]]\" to \"fighting a local war under hi-tech conditions.\" The PLA planners believed that the next war would be a short, fast-paced conflict on the periphery rather than a total war on Chinese territory, and that conventional [[infantry]]-orientated ground forces would no longer meet their requirements. Additionally, the PLA's combat experience from the [[Sino-Vietnamese War|1979 and 1980s border conflicts with Vietnam]], where Vietnamese [[special forces]] caused substantial trouble to the Chinese forces, demonstrated the value of special units.\n\nOn 23 December 2008, their first publicly known mission was to accompany three Chinese warships in protecting and escorting commercial ships against [[piracy in Somalia|Somali pirates]], in cooperation with other nations as part of a UN mandate.<ref>[http://www.defencetalk.com/news/publish/navy/China_ready_to_use_force_on_Somali_pirates120016822.php] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081225103150/http://www.defencetalk.com/news/publish/navy/China_ready_to_use_force_on_Somali_pirates120016822.php|date=December 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Special Operations Forces Units ==\n[[File:140716-G-HN254-571 (14714332244).jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|People's Liberation Army Navy Special Forces]]\n\n* Beijing Military Region \u2013 \"Oriental Sword\". All 3,000 soldiers in this unit can complete all types of operations and are regarded as the elite arm of the country.<ref name=\"china.org\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.china.org/ |title={title} |access-date=2018-10-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180809171529/http://china.org/ |archive-date=2018-08-09 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Beijing Military Region Special Forces Unit \u2013 \"Arrow\". Established in the early 1990s, this unit is equipped with high-tech equipment including unmanned aerial reconnaissance vehicles (UARVs), individual blast devices and handheld laser dazzling weapons. Every soldier from this unit must be able to run five kilometers bearing heavy equipment in under 25 minutes, complete a 400-meter obstacle course in under one minute and 45 seconds, perform 100 push-ups in a minute, and repeatedly throw [[grenade]]s more than {{convert|50|m|ft}}.<ref name=\"wantchinatimes.com\"/>\n* Guangzhou Military Region Special Forces Unit \u2013 \"South Blade\" or \"South China Sword\". This unit was established in 1988 as the PLA's first special reconnaissance group. It was expanded in 2000 to become the first PLA special operations unit to be capable of air-, sea-, and land-operations, similar to [[United States Navy SEALs|U.S. Navy SEALs]]. Basic training for this unit includes cross-country running, climbing, swimming and shooting. The soldiers must also be familiar with operating 15 advanced technologies including GPS navigation, night vision, and photo reconnaissance.<ref name=\"wantchinatimes.com\">{{cite web |url = http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20141219000062&cid=1101 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-10-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150630150416/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20141219000062&cid=1101 |archivedate=2015-06-30 }}</ref>\n* Chengdu Military Region Special Forces Unit \u2013 Falcon. Established in 1992, this unit is specialized in target locating and indicating, airborne insertion, sabotage and offensive strikes, and emergency evacuation. The unit was also used by Chengdu Military Region to experiment with new advanced concept equipment and tactics, including the digitized army soldier system and high-mobility land weapon platforms.\n* Shenyang Military Region Special Forces Unit \u2013 Siberian Tiger\". This unit is trained to complete missions on the ground and in the air and water, as well as surviving in the wilderness alone or in small groups. The unit is said to place special focus on survival skills; it often breaks protocol by increasing this training by two-thirds, forcing soldiers to spend three to four months in difficult environments such as forests, mountains, deserts and grasslands with no man-made shelter or food. Soldiers in the unit are trained on multiple transport vehicles for roads, railroads, waterways, and in the air. Individual members of the unit have reportedly completed parachute landings more than 5,000 times and logged scuba diving training of more than 1,000 hours.<ref name=\"wantchinatimes.com\" />\n* Nanjing Military Region Special Forces Unit \u2013 Flying Dragon. This is the special land force of east China's Nanjing Military Region.\n* Nanjing Military Region Special Forces Unit \u2013 Oscar.\n* Lanzhou Military Region Special Forces Unit \u2013 Night Tiger. This unit has a long history, with its origins dating back to World War II. It is the home of China's first counter-terrorism unit, established in 2000.<ref name=\"wantchinatimes.com\" />\n* Jinan Military Region Special Forces Unit \u2013 Eagle. Soldiers from this unit are said to focus on training to enhance cardiovascular endurance, including being able to run at least 3,300 meters in under 12 minutes. They also reportedly engage in hand-to-hand combat training and the traditional Chinese health and martial arts practice of [[Qigong]].<ref name=\"wantchinatimes.com\" /> Soldiers of the Eagle special force can complete sea-air-land operations,<ref name=\"china.org\"/> in a similar way to the U.S. Navy SEALs.\n* Leishen (Thundergod) Commando Airborne Force is trained for reconnaissance operations for the PLA's airborne units. It is capable of performing strategic deterrence, combat assault, and task operations under IT-based conditions. Members of this unit recently attended the Golden Owl-2015 International Competition of Special Forces held in Kazakhstan, and won first place.<ref name=\"220.181.168.86\">{{cite web |url = http://220.181.168.86/NewJsp/news.jsp?fileId=305427 |title = H OME-CCTVPLUS |website = 220.181.168.86 |access-date = 2016-06-05 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160701042345/http://220.181.168.86/NewJsp/news.jsp?fileId=305427 |archive-date = 2016-07-01 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref name=\"english.chinamil.com.cn\">{{cite web |url = http://english.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2015-07/10/content_6581621.htm |title = Chinese airborne troops win glory in int'l special forces competition |first = Yao |last = Jianing |website = english.chinamil.com.cn |access-date = 2015-09-20 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160305034959/http://english.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2015-07/10/content_6581621.htm |archive-date = 2016-03-05 |url-status = live }}</ref> Representatives also attended the Russia International Army Games in 2015 where they took first place in the Airborne Platoon competition. Ten teams, from Kazakhstan, Belarus, China, Russia, Indonesia and Singapore, attended the competition.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |url=http://english.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2015-08/06/content_6617856.htm |title=Chinese team ranks first in first stage of Airborne Platoon competition |first=Yao |last=Jianing |website=english.chinamil.com.cn |access-date=2016-06-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111201300/http://english.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2015-08/06/content_6617856.htm |archive-date=2017-01-11 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[People's Liberation Navy|Sea Dragon]] is the [[People's Liberation Army Navy]] commando force. Members of this force are equipped with black uniforms. Its first publicly known mission was to accompany three Chinese warships in protecting and escorting commercial ships against Somali pirates in December 2008, in cooperation with other nations as part of a UN mandate. Since then, the unit has participated in anti-piracy missions in the [[Gulf of Aden]] for over 300 days.<ref name=\"wantchinatimes.com\"/> Sea Dragon's Jiaolong Assault Team helped evacuate 225 foreign nationals and almost 600 Chinese citizens from Yemen's southern port of Aden during late March 2015, during the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://en.chinagate.cn/2015-04/08/content_35270564.htm | title=Feature: Chinese naval vessels evacuate hundreds from war-torn Yemen -- China Development Gateway -- Sharing Information, Knowledge and Tools}}</ref>\n* The Southwest China Falcon special force is known as Leopard.<ref name=\"china.org\" />\n\n== Awards ==\n* 2009 international military competitions in [[Slovakia]] \u2013 8-first places, 6-second places in 13 individual competition events.<ref name=\"chinamil1\">{{cite web |url = http://eng.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2010-02/23/content_4140376.htm |title=Chinese NCO flaunts might in international military competition |publisher=Eng.chinamil.com.cn |date=2010-02-23 |accessdate=2012-02-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120822233503/http://eng.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2010-02/23/content_4140376.htm |archivedate=2012-08-22 }}</ref>\n* Third place in the 2010 Sniper World Cup and first place in the 2011 Sniper World Cup.<ref name=\"chinadaily1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2011-05/31/content_12608539.htm |title=China dominates Military and Police Sniper World Cup |publisher=Chinadaily.com.cn |date=2011-05-31 |accessdate=2012-02-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120914025849/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2011-05/31/content_12608539.htm |archive-date=2012-09-14 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Best overall performance at the fifth and sixth Warrior Competition, organized by the Jordan Armed Forces at the King Abdullah II Special Operations Training Centre.<ref name=\"Qamar\">{{cite web |url = http://chinesemilitaryreview.blogspot.com/2013/03/chinese-special-operations-forces-sof.html |title = Chinese Special Operation Team Wins First Position At International Special Forces Contest |first = M. J. |last = Qamar |access-date = 2015-05-12 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170807153852/http://chinesemilitaryreview.blogspot.com/2013/03/chinese-special-operations-forces-sof.html |archive-date = 2017-08-07 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.all4shooters.com/en/home/pro-zone/2014-news/Kasotc-annual-warrior-competition/ |title = Snow Leopard Unit wins 6th Annual Warrior Competition - Pro-zone - Pro-zone - News - all4shooters.com |first = all4shooters.com / Photos |last = KASOTC |website = all4shooters.com |language = en |access-date = 2015-05-03 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150423054406/http://www.all4shooters.com/en/home/pro-zone/2014-news/Kasotc-annual-warrior-competition/ |archive-date = 2015-04-23 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n* Chinese Special Forces took first place at the 2013 fifth International Warrior Competition, organized by the Jordan Armed Forces at the King Abdullah II Special Operations Training Centre.<ref name=\"Qamar\" />\n* Chinese Special Forces took first, second, and fourth place at 2014 Olympics for Elite Warriors.<ref>Jeffrey Lin and P.W. Singer,Popular Science,Eastern Arsenal</ref> \n* Chinese Thor (Leishen) Commando Airborne troops participated in the Golden Owl-2015 International Competition of Special Forces held in Kazakhstan, taking first place.<ref name=\"220.181.168.86\"/><ref name=\"english.chinamil.com.cn\"/> They also attended the Russia International Army Games in 2015 where they took first place in the \"Airborne Platoon\" competition.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n* China's Sky Sword Unit placed first in the ninth edition of the 2017 [[Annual Warrior Competition]] in Amman, Jordon.<ref name=\"Event - Annual Warrior Competition\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.warriorcompetition.com/Pages/viewpage.aspx?pageID=25&ID=56 |title=Event - Annual Warrior Competition |access-date=2018-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130091246/http://www.warriorcompetition.com/Pages/viewpage.aspx?pageID=25&ID=56 |archive-date=2018-01-30 |url-status=live }}</ref> China's Falcon Commando Unit placed third overall in the competition.<ref name=\"Event - Annual Warrior Competition\"/> Thirty-one teams from seventeen nations participated in the competition.\n* China' Snow Leopards team placed second in the tenth edition of the 2018 Annual Warrior Competition in Amman, Jordon.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.joint-forces.com/world-news/13670-10th-annual-warrior-competition-results |title=10th Annual Warrior Competition ~ Results |access-date=2018-08-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180807220523/http://www.joint-forces.com/world-news/13670-10th-annual-warrior-competition-results |archive-date=2018-08-07 |url-status=live |date=2018-05-07 }}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\n* In the 1998 ''[[Hong Kong]]'' film ''[[Another Meltdown]]'' AKA ''[[Blacksheep Affair]]''. The main character Yim Dong played by Chinese actor and martial artist ''[[Vincent Zhao]]'' is a ''[[People's Armed Police]]'' officer sent to eastern europe after disobeying orders as punishment during a plane hijacking in ''[[Shenzhen]]''. There he ends up in conflict with a Japanese terrorist cultist bombing the area and he and several PLA SOF commandos end up escorting the Japanese maniac to prison but end up fighting off several ''[[Sicilian Mafia]]'' thugs and Japanese Cultists resembling the Japanese ''[[Aleph]]' off in an intense ambush.\n\n* Rogue PLA SOF appear in the late levels working under a rogue Chinese military general Wu Xing in the 2003 video game ''[[IGI 2 Covert Strike]]'' . A game which ended up banned in China due to \"intentionally blackening China's image\"\n\n* In the 2005 video game ''[[Battlefield 2 Modern Combat]]'' the PLA SOF are playable in the China Campaign levels under the command of Colonel Yuanheng Zhu, and even have the player decide who wins the conflict between NATO and China during the campaign finale.\n\n* The PLA Special Operations Forces are a playable Counter Terrorist team in the 2008 online multiplayer shooter ''[[Counter-Strike Online]]'' .\n\n* Some PLA SOF appear in the 2008 video game ''[[Mercenaries 2: World in Flames]]'' under the command of General Zhou Peng who was promoted from the first game's events, and can either be allies or enemies depending on whether the player sides with the Allied or Chinese forces invading Venezuela.\n\n* The PLA Special Operations Forces have brief appearances in the 2009 Japanese anime ''[[CANAAN]]'' . Their appearance is very brief as they are seen escorting Doctor Kenji \u014csawa to safety in the anime during a terrorist attack.\n\n* PLA Special Operations Forces are featured as the protagonists in the Chinese 2011 Military first person shooter game  developed by Giant Interactive Group called ''[[Glorious Mission]]'' who fight enemies resembling ''[[United States Armed Forces]]'', ''[[Japanese Self Defense Forces]]'' and the ''[[Philippine Army]]'' .\n\n* PLA SOF appear in the 2012 video game  ''[[Call of Duty: Black Ops II]]'' but as the fictional Strategic Defense Coalition under the command of General Tian Zhao voiced and mo-capped by actor ''[[Byron Mann]]''. Depending on the player's action's during the games Strike missions, the SDC end up either assisting the player or remaining enemies for the rest of the game.\n\n* PLA SOF appear in the 2013 video game  ''[[Battlefield 4]]'' but as the main Antagonistic force, under the command of a rogue military Admiral Wei Chang. They are also a playable faction in the games online multiplayer. The game was banned in China for developing content that threatens the country's national security accusations that the U.S. game developer ''[[Electronic Arts]]'' depicted a form of cultural invasion on the country.\n\n* PLA SOF appear briefly in the 2014 ''[[Taiwan]]'' film ''[[Black & White: The Dawn of Justice]]'' a sequel to ''[[Black & White Episode I: The Dawn of Assault]]'' and prequel to the 2009 Taiwanese drama ''[[Black & White (TV series)|Black & White]]''. The PLA SOF are in a convoy and mistaken the protagonists Officer Wu Ying Xiong played by ''[[Mark Chao]]'' and Officer Chen Zhen played by ''[[Lin Gengxin]]'' as attackers and detain them. However the PLA SOF convoy is quickly ambushed by rogue Taiwanese black ops operatives and suffer mass casualties despite Wu Ying Xiong and Chen Zhen trying to assist them. \n\n* In the 2015 Chinese surprise hit movie  ''[[Wolf Warrior]]'', the PLA SOF are portrayed as an elite military unit called the Wolf Warriors who fight off several foreign American and European mercenaries who have infiltrated China. The main character Leng Feng played by actor ''[[Wu Jing (actor)]]'' ends up being recruited into the Wolves.\n\n* Some PLA SOF operators called the Wild Bulls assist a Chinese Narco team lead by Captain Gao Gang played by ''[[Zhang Hanyu]]'' raiding a Burmese pirate encampment during the finale of the 2016 Chinese film ''[[Operation Mekong]]'' . Based on the 2011 ''[[Mekong River massacre]]'' on Chinese fishermen.\n\n* PLA SOF operators raid a terrorist base in the fictional country of the Republic of Mahbu in the 2017 Chinese airforce film ''[[Sky Hunter]]''  .\n\n* Sea Dragon's elite Jiaolong Assault Team is featured in the 2018 cinematic release ''[[Operation Red Sea]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2018/01/14/operation-red-sea-soundtrack-details/ |title='Operation Red Sea' Soundtrack Details &#124; Film Music Reporter |access-date=2018-09-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825220528/http://filmmusicreporter.com/2018/01/14/operation-red-sea-soundtrack-details/ |archive-date=2018-08-25 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film is loosely based on the evacuation of the 225 foreign nationals and almost 600 Chinese citizens from Yemen's southern port of Aden during late March in 2015 during the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://english.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2015-07/10/content_6581621.htm\n* http://220.181.168.86/NewJsp/news.jsp?fileId=305427\n* http://english.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2015-08/06/content_6617856.htm\n* http://www.popsci.com/which-latin-american-country-did-china-just-send-commandos\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070516053143/http://www.sinodefence.com/organisation/groundforces/specialoperations.asp Sinodefence.com]\n* http://www.china.org.cn/top10/2014-12/18/content_34348497.htm\n* http://drrichswier.com/2014/05/27/u-s-special-operations-forces-special/\n* http://english.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2015-07/10/content_6581621.htm\n\n{{-}}\n{{People's Liberation Army}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations of the People's Republic of China]]\n[[Category:People's Liberation Army Ground Force]]\n[[Category:Special forces of the People's Republic of China| ]]\n[[Category:Counter-terrorist organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chinese Special Operations Forces}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name = People's Liberation Army Special Operations Forces\n|native_name= \u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u6c11\u89e3\u653e\u519b\u7279\u79cd\u90e8\u961f\n|image = Pla ensign sof.jpg\n|image_size = 200\n|caption = An example of PLA Special Operations Forces insignia\n|dates = 1988 \u2013 Present\n|allegiance = [[File:Flag_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party.svg|23px]] [[Communist Party of China]]\n|country = {{Flag|People's Republic of China}}\n|branch = {{Flagicon image|Ground Force Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|size=23px}} [[People's Liberation Army Ground Force]]<br />{{Flagicon image|Naval Ensign of the People's Republic of China.svg|size=23px}} [[People's Liberation Army Navy]]<br />{{Flagicon image|Air Force Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|size=23px}} [[People's Liberation Army Air Force]]<br />{{Flagicon image|Rocket Force Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|size=23px}} [[People's Liberation Army Rocket Force]]\n|type = [[Special forces]]\n|command_structure =\n|role = [[Special operations]]<br />[[Counter-terrorism]]<br />[[Military intelligence]]<br />(Deployable & operational from land, air and sea)\n|size= [[Classified information|Classified]]; Analysts believe current size is between 7,000 and 14,000 troops.{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n|current_commander =\n|garrison =\n|ceremonial_chief =\n|ceremonial_chief_label =\n|colonel_of_the_regiment = \n|nickname =\n|motto =\n|colors =\n|march =\n|mascot =\n|battles= [[Piracy in Somalia|Counter-piracy operations]]\n|notable_commanders =\n|anniversaries =\n}}\n\nThe '''People's Liberation Army special operations forces''' ({{zh\n|s = \u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u6c11\u89e3\u653e\u519b\u7279\u79cd\u90e8\u961f\n|t = \u4e2d\u570b\u4eba\u6c11\u89e3\u653e\u8ecd\u7279\u7a2e\u90e8\u968a\n|p = Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 R\u00e9nm\u00edn Ji\u011bf\u00e0ngj\u016bn t\u00e8zh\u01d2ng b\u00f9du\u00ec }}) are the [[special forces]] of the [[People's Republic of China|Chinese]] [[People's Liberation Army]] (PLA). The size of the Special Operations Forces is estimated to be between 7,000 and 14,000 troops. The forces intended combat role is as rapid-response units in the event of a limited regional war under high-tech conditions. They also carry out commando, counter-terrorism, and intelligence gathering operations. \n\nThe building up of China's special forces represents a shift in the country's operational thinking, from an army-dominated force structure to emphasizing integrated joint operations, with a flexible elite force.\n\n== History ==\nThe PLA's interest in modern special warfare was first noted in the mid-1980s when it was shifting its military stance from a \"[[people's war]]\" to \"fighting a local war under hi-tech conditions.\" The PLA planners believed that the next war would be a short, fast-paced conflict on the periphery rather than a total war on Chinese territory, and that conventional [[infantry]]-orientated ground forces would no longer meet their requirements. Additionally, the PLA's combat experience from the [[Sino-Vietnamese War|1979 and 1980s border conflicts with Vietnam]], where Vietnamese [[special forces]] caused substantial trouble to the Chinese forces, demonstrated the value of special units.\n\nOn 23 December 2008, their first publicly known mission was to accompany three Chinese warships in protecting and escorting commercial ships against [[piracy in Somalia|Somali pirates]], in cooperation with other nations as part of a UN mandate.<ref>[http://www.defencetalk.com/news/publish/navy/China_ready_to_use_force_on_Somali_pirates120016822.php] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081225103150/http://www.defencetalk.com/news/publish/navy/China_ready_to_use_force_on_Somali_pirates120016822.php|date=December 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Special Operations Forces Units ==\n[[File:140716-G-HN254-571 (14714332244).jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|People's Liberation Army Navy Special Forces]]\n\n* Beijing Military Region \u2013 \"Oriental Sword\". All 3,000 soldiers in this unit can complete all types of operations and are regarded as the elite arm of the country.<ref name=\"china.org\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.china.org/ |title={title} |access-date=2018-10-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180809171529/http://china.org/ |archive-date=2018-08-09 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Beijing Military Region Special Forces Unit \u2013 \"Arrow\". Established in the early 1990s, this unit is equipped with high-tech equipment including unmanned aerial reconnaissance vehicles (UARVs), individual blast devices and handheld laser dazzling weapons. Every soldier from this unit must be able to run five kilometers bearing heavy equipment in under 25 minutes, complete a 400-meter obstacle course in under one minute and 45 seconds, perform 100 push-ups in a minute, and repeatedly throw [[grenade]]s more than {{convert|50|m|ft}}.<ref name=\"wantchinatimes.com\"/>\n* Guangzhou Military Region Special Forces Unit \u2013 \"South Blade\" or \"South China Sword\". This unit was established in 1988 as the PLA's first special reconnaissance group. It was expanded in 2000 to become the first PLA special operations unit to be capable of air-, sea-, and land-operations, similar to [[United States Navy SEALs|U.S. Navy SEALs]]. Basic training for this unit includes cross-country running, climbing, swimming and shooting. The soldiers must also be familiar with operating 15 advanced technologies including GPS navigation, night vision, and photo reconnaissance.<ref name=\"wantchinatimes.com\">{{cite web |url = http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20141219000062&cid=1101 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-10-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150630150416/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20141219000062&cid=1101 |archivedate=2015-06-30 }}</ref>\n* Chengdu Military Region Special Forces Unit \u2013 Falcon. Established in 1992, this unit is specialized in target locating and indicating, airborne insertion, sabotage and offensive strikes, and emergency evacuation. The unit was also used by Chengdu Military Region to experiment with new advanced concept equipment and tactics, including the digitized army soldier system and high-mobility land weapon platforms.\n* Shenyang Military Region Special Forces Unit \u2013 Siberian Tiger\". This unit is trained to complete missions on the ground and in the air and water, as well as surviving in the wilderness alone or in small groups. The unit is said to place special focus on survival skills; it often breaks protocol by increasing this training by two-thirds, forcing soldiers to spend three to four months in difficult environments such as forests, mountains, deserts and grasslands with no man-made shelter or food. Soldiers in the unit are trained on multiple transport vehicles for roads, railroads, waterways, and in the air. Individual members of the unit have reportedly completed parachute landings more than 5,000 times and logged scuba diving training of more than 1,000 hours.<ref name=\"wantchinatimes.com\" />\n* Nanjing Military Region Special Forces Unit \u2013 Flying Dragon. This is the special land force of east China's Nanjing Military Region.\n* Nanjing Military Region Special Forces Unit \u2013 Oscar.\n* Lanzhou Military Region Special Forces Unit \u2013 Night Tiger. This unit has a long history, with its origins dating back to World War II. It is the home of China's first counter-terrorism unit, established in 2000.<ref name=\"wantchinatimes.com\" />\n* Jinan Military Region Special Forces Unit \u2013 Eagle. Soldiers from this unit are said to focus on training to enhance cardiovascular endurance, including being able to run at least 3,300 meters in under 12 minutes. They also reportedly engage in hand-to-hand combat training and the traditional Chinese health and martial arts practice of [[Qigong]].<ref name=\"wantchinatimes.com\" /> Soldiers of the Eagle special force can complete sea-air-land operations,<ref name=\"china.org\"/> in a similar way to the U.S. Navy SEALs.\n* Leishen (Thundergod) Commando Airborne Force is trained for reconnaissance operations for the PLA's airborne units. It is capable of performing strategic deterrence, combat assault, and task operations under IT-based conditions. Members of this unit recently attended the Golden Owl-2015 International Competition of Special Forces held in Kazakhstan, and won first place.<ref name=\"220.181.168.86\">{{cite web |url = http://220.181.168.86/NewJsp/news.jsp?fileId=305427 |title = H OME-CCTVPLUS |website = 220.181.168.86 |access-date = 2016-06-05 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160701042345/http://220.181.168.86/NewJsp/news.jsp?fileId=305427 |archive-date = 2016-07-01 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref name=\"english.chinamil.com.cn\">{{cite web |url = http://english.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2015-07/10/content_6581621.htm |title = Chinese airborne troops win glory in int'l special forces competition |first = Yao |last = Jianing |website = english.chinamil.com.cn |access-date = 2015-09-20 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160305034959/http://english.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2015-07/10/content_6581621.htm |archive-date = 2016-03-05 |url-status = live }}</ref> Representatives also attended the Russia International Army Games in 2015 where they took first place in the Airborne Platoon competition. Ten teams, from Kazakhstan, Belarus, China, Russia, Indonesia and Singapore, attended the competition.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |url=http://english.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2015-08/06/content_6617856.htm |title=Chinese team ranks first in first stage of Airborne Platoon competition |first=Yao |last=Jianing |website=english.chinamil.com.cn |access-date=2016-06-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111201300/http://english.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2015-08/06/content_6617856.htm |archive-date=2017-01-11 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[People's Liberation Navy|Sea Dragon]] is the [[People's Liberation Army Navy]] commando force. Members of this force are equipped with black uniforms. Its first publicly known mission was to accompany three Chinese warships in protecting and escorting commercial ships against Somali pirates in December 2008, in cooperation with other nations as part of a UN mandate. Since then, the unit has participated in anti-piracy missions in the [[Gulf of Aden]] for over 300 days.<ref name=\"wantchinatimes.com\"/> Sea Dragon's Jiaolong Assault Team helped evacuate 225 foreign nationals and almost 600 Chinese citizens from Yemen's southern port of Aden during late March 2015, during the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://en.chinagate.cn/2015-04/08/content_35270564.htm | title=Feature: Chinese naval vessels evacuate hundreds from war-torn Yemen -- China Development Gateway -- Sharing Information, Knowledge and Tools}}</ref>\n* The Southwest China Falcon special force is known as Leopard.<ref name=\"china.org\" />\n\n== Awards ==\n* 2009 international military competitions in [[Slovakia]] \u2013 8-first places, 6-second places in 13 individual competition events.<ref name=\"chinamil1\">{{cite web |url = http://eng.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2010-02/23/content_4140376.htm |title=Chinese NCO flaunts might in international military competition |publisher=Eng.chinamil.com.cn |date=2010-02-23 |accessdate=2012-02-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120822233503/http://eng.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2010-02/23/content_4140376.htm |archivedate=2012-08-22 }}</ref>\n* Third place in the 2010 Sniper World Cup and first place in the 2011 Sniper World Cup.<ref name=\"chinadaily1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2011-05/31/content_12608539.htm |title=China dominates Military and Police Sniper World Cup |publisher=Chinadaily.com.cn |date=2011-05-31 |accessdate=2012-02-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120914025849/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2011-05/31/content_12608539.htm |archive-date=2012-09-14 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Best overall performance at the fifth and sixth Warrior Competition, organized by the Jordan Armed Forces at the King Abdullah II Special Operations Training Centre.<ref name=\"Qamar\">{{cite web |url = http://chinesemilitaryreview.blogspot.com/2013/03/chinese-special-operations-forces-sof.html |title = Chinese Special Operation Team Wins First Position At International Special Forces Contest |first = M. J. |last = Qamar |access-date = 2015-05-12 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170807153852/http://chinesemilitaryreview.blogspot.com/2013/03/chinese-special-operations-forces-sof.html |archive-date = 2017-08-07 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.all4shooters.com/en/home/pro-zone/2014-news/Kasotc-annual-warrior-competition/ |title = Snow Leopard Unit wins 6th Annual Warrior Competition - Pro-zone - Pro-zone - News - all4shooters.com |first = all4shooters.com / Photos |last = KASOTC |website = all4shooters.com |language = en |access-date = 2015-05-03 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150423054406/http://www.all4shooters.com/en/home/pro-zone/2014-news/Kasotc-annual-warrior-competition/ |archive-date = 2015-04-23 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n* Chinese Special Forces took first place at the 2013 fifth International Warrior Competition, organized by the Jordan Armed Forces at the King Abdullah II Special Operations Training Centre.<ref name=\"Qamar\" />\n* Chinese Special Forces took first, second, and fourth place at 2014 Olympics for Elite Warriors.<ref>Jeffrey Lin and P.W. Singer,Popular Science,Eastern Arsenal</ref> \n* Chinese Thor (Leishen) Commando Airborne troops participated in the Golden Owl-2015 International Competition of Special Forces held in Kazakhstan, taking first place.<ref name=\"220.181.168.86\"/><ref name=\"english.chinamil.com.cn\"/> They also attended the Russia International Army Games in 2015 where they took first place in the \"Airborne Platoon\" competition.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n* China's Sky Sword Unit placed first in the ninth edition of the 2017 [[Annual Warrior Competition]] in Amman, Jordon.<ref name=\"Event - Annual Warrior Competition\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.warriorcompetition.com/Pages/viewpage.aspx?pageID=25&ID=56 |title=Event - Annual Warrior Competition |access-date=2018-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130091246/http://www.warriorcompetition.com/Pages/viewpage.aspx?pageID=25&ID=56 |archive-date=2018-01-30 |url-status=live }}</ref> China's Falcon Commando Unit placed third overall in the competition.<ref name=\"Event - Annual Warrior Competition\"/> Thirty-one teams from seventeen nations participated in the competition.\n* China' Snow Leopards team placed second in the tenth edition of the 2018 Annual Warrior Competition in Amman, Jordon.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.joint-forces.com/world-news/13670-10th-annual-warrior-competition-results |title=10th Annual Warrior Competition ~ Results |access-date=2018-08-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180807220523/http://www.joint-forces.com/world-news/13670-10th-annual-warrior-competition-results |archive-date=2018-08-07 |url-status=live |date=2018-05-07 }}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\n* In the 1998 ''[[Hong Kong]]'' film ''[[Another Meltdown]]'' AKA ''[[Blacksheep Affair]]''. The main character Yim Dong played by Chinese actor and martial artist ''[[Vincent Zhao]]'' is a ''[[People's Armed Police]]'' officer sent to eastern europe after disobeying orders as punishment during a plane hijacking in ''[[Shenzhen]]''. There he ends up in conflict with a Japanese terrorist cultist bombing the area and he and several PLA SOF commandos end up escorting the Japanese maniac to prison but end up fighting off several ''[[Sicilian Mafia]]'' thugs and Japanese Cultists resembling the Japanese ''[[Aleph]]' off in an intense ambush.\n\n* Rogue PLA SOF appear in the late levels working under a rogue Chinese military general Wu Xing in the 2003 video game ''[[IGI 2 Covert Strike]]'' . A game which ended up banned in China due to \"intentionally blackening China's image\"\n\n* In the 2005 video game ''[[Battlefield 2 Modern Combat]]'' the PLA SOF are playable in the China Campaign levels under the command of Colonel Yuanheng Zhu, and even have the player decide who wins the conflict between NATO and China during the campaign finale.\n\n* The PLA Special Operations Forces are a playable Counter Terrorist team in the 2008 online multiplayer shooter ''[[Counter-Strike Online]]'' .\n\n* Some PLA SOF appear in the 2008 video game ''[[Mercenaries 2: World in Flames]]'' under the command of General Zhou Peng who was promoted from the first game's events, and can either be allies or enemies depending on whether the player sides with the Allied or Chinese forces invading Venezuela.\n\n* The PLA Special Operations Forces have brief appearances in the 2009 Japanese anime ''[[CANAAN]]'' . Their appearance is very brief as they are seen escorting Doctor Kenji \u014csawa to safety in the anime during a terrorist attack.\n\n* PLA Special Operations Forces are featured as the protagonists in the Chinese 2011 Military first person shooter game  developed by Giant Interactive Group called ''[[Glorious Mission]]'' who fight enemies resembling ''[[United States Armed Forces]]'', ''[[Japanese Self Defense Forces]]'' and the ''[[Philippine Army]]'' .\n\n* PLA SOF appear in the 2012 video game  ''[[Call of Duty: Black Ops II]]'' but as the fictional Strategic Defense Coalition under the command of General Tian Zhao voiced and mo-capped by actor ''[[Byron Mann]]''. Depending on the player's action's during the games Strike missions, the SDC end up either assisting the player or remaining enemies for the rest of the game.\n\n* PLA SOF appear in the 2013 video game  ''[[Battlefield 4]]'' but as the main Antagonistic force, under the command of a rogue military Admiral Wei Chang. They are also a playable faction in the games online multiplayer. The game was banned in China for developing content that threatens the country's national security accusations that the U.S. game developer ''[[Electronic Arts]]'' depicted a form of cultural invasion on the country.\n\n* PLA SOF appear briefly in the 2014 ''[[Taiwan]]'' film ''[[Black & White: The Dawn of Justice]]'' a sequel to ''[[Black & White Episode I: The Dawn of Assault]]'' and prequel to the 2009 Taiwanese drama ''[[Black & White]]''. The PLA SOF are in a convoy and mistaken the protagonists Officer Wu Ying Xiong played by ''[[Mark Chao]]'' and Officer Chen Zhen played by ''[[Lin Gengxin]]'' as attackers and detain them. However the PLA SOF convoy is quickly ambushed by rogue Taiwanese black ops operatives and suffer mass casualties despite Wu Ying Xiong and Chen Zhen trying to assist them. \n\n* In the 2015 Chinese surprise hit movie  ''[[Wolf Warrior]]'', the PLA SOF are portrayed as an elite military unit called the Wolf Warriors who fight off several foreign American and European mercenaries who have infiltrated China. The main character Leng Feng played by actor ''[[Wu Jing (actor)]]'' ends up being recruited into the Wolves.\n\n* Some PLA SOF operators called the Wild Bulls assist a Chinese Narco team lead by Captain Gao Gang played by ''[[Zhang Hanyu]]'' raiding a Burmese pirate encampment during the finale of the 2016 Chinese film ''[[Operation Mekong]]'' . Based on the 2011 ''[[Mekong River massacre]]'' on Chinese fishermen.\n\n* PLA SOF operators raid a terrorist base in the fictional country of the Republic of Mahbu in the 2017 Chinese airforce film ''[[Sky Hunter]]''  .\n\n* Sea Dragon's elite Jiaolong Assault Team is featured in the 2018 cinematic release ''[[Operation Red Sea]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2018/01/14/operation-red-sea-soundtrack-details/ |title='Operation Red Sea' Soundtrack Details &#124; Film Music Reporter |access-date=2018-09-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825220528/http://filmmusicreporter.com/2018/01/14/operation-red-sea-soundtrack-details/ |archive-date=2018-08-25 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film is loosely based on the evacuation of the 225 foreign nationals and almost 600 Chinese citizens from Yemen's southern port of Aden during late March in 2015 during the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://english.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2015-07/10/content_6581621.htm\n* http://220.181.168.86/NewJsp/news.jsp?fileId=305427\n* http://english.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2015-08/06/content_6617856.htm\n* http://www.popsci.com/which-latin-american-country-did-china-just-send-commandos\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070516053143/http://www.sinodefence.com/organisation/groundforces/specialoperations.asp Sinodefence.com]\n* http://www.china.org.cn/top10/2014-12/18/content_34348497.htm\n* http://drrichswier.com/2014/05/27/u-s-special-operations-forces-special/\n* http://english.chinamil.com.cn/news-channels/china-military-news/2015-07/10/content_6581621.htm\n\n{{-}}\n{{People's Liberation Army}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations of the People's Republic of China]]\n[[Category:People's Liberation Army Ground Force]]\n[[Category:Special forces of the People's Republic of China| ]]\n[[Category:Counter-terrorist organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Black & White\u2192Black & White (TV series)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/People%27s_Liberation_Army_Special_Operations_Forces"}
