ld War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Barents Sea]] ({{coord|73|44|N|27|12|E}}) by [[Fairey Swordfish]] aircraft of [[819 Naval Air Squadron|819 Squadron]], [[Fleet Air Arm]], based on {{HMS|Activity|D94|6}} and [[Grumman TBM Avenger]] and [[Grumman F4F Wildcat]] aircraft of [[846 Naval Air Squadron|846 Squadron]], Fleet Air Arm based on {{HMS|Tracker|D24|6}} (both {{navy|UK}}) with the loss of all 49 crew.<ref name=U288>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u288.htm |title=U-288 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=14 March 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==4 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=4 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Choun Maru||2}} \n|flag={{army|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The transport was sunk in an air raid on [[Rabaul]], [[New Guinea]] by Consolidated B-24 Liberator and [[North American B-25 Mitchell]] aircraft of the United States [[Thirteenth Air Force]].<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref name=USNChron1944>{{cite web |url=https://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/USN-Chron/USN-Chron-1944.html |title=USN chronology 1944 |publisher=www.ibiblio.org |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Jsub|I-169||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The [[Kaidai-class submarine|''Kaidai''-class submarine]] was sunk in a diving accident north-west of Dublon Island, Truk, during an air raid by [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator|Consolidated PBY-4 Liberator]] aircraft. All aboard died. 32 bodies were recovered in the following weeks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/I-169.htm |title=I-169 |publisher=www.combinedfleet.com |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Iwakuni Maru||2}} \n|flag={{army|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The transport was sunk in an air raid on Rabaul by Consolidated B-25 Liberator and North American B-25 Mitchell aircraft of the United States Thirteenth Air Force. 32 crew members were killed.<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref name=USNChron1944/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hush.gooside.com/Text/0A/02I/I80aIwa_.html |title=Iwakuni Maru |publisher=hush.gooside.com |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|I-O-10||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}} \n|desc=The ''Siebelgef\u00e4\u00df'' landing craft was sunk on this date.<ref name=\"Navypedia\"/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minesweeper|Sperrbrecher 157||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The ''[[Sperrbrecher]]'' struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and was severely damaged off [[Brest, France|Brest]], [[Finist\u00e8re]], France.<ref name=seekrieg194404/> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==5 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=5 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese auxiliary submarine chaser|CHa-46||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The [[No.1-class auxiliary submarine chaser|''CHa-1''-class]] auxiliary [[submarine chaser]] was sunk at [[Wake Island]] by [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator]] aircraft of VB-109, [[United States Navy]].<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref name=\"1-Go auxiliary submarine chasers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/japan/jap_sc_aux.htm |title=1-Go auxiliary submarine chasers |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minesweeper|R-261||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[R boat|Type R-218 minesweeper]] was sunk off [[Boulogne-sur-Mer|Boulogne]], [[Pas-de-Calais]], France by Allied aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=765 |title=German coastal minesweeper Type R-218 |publisher=Warshipsww2.Eu |accessdate=3 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513052207/http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=756 |archive-date=13 May 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Tenryu Maru||2}} \n|flag={{army|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The transport was sunk in an air raid on Rabaul by Consolidated B-25 Liberator and North American B-25 Mitchell aircraft of the United States Thirteenth Air Force with the loss of 28 lives.<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hush.gooside.com/name/t/Te/Tenryu/Tenryu.html#anchor97346 |title=Tenryu Maru |publisher=hush.gooside.com |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German yacht|UJ 6070 Cetonia||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The armed yacht/submarine chaser was lost on this date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_conc_yachts.htm |title=Armed Yachts of WWII, Converted Merchant Ships, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=19 April 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|YT-247}} \n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=The harbor tug was swamped and foundered {{convert|425|nmi|km}} south west of [[Oahu]], [[Hawaii]] ({{coord|14|14|N|158|59|E}}) while under tow from [[Pearl Harbor]] to [[Palmyra Island]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/USN-Chron/USN-Chron-1944.html |title=Official Cronology of the US Navy in WWII |publisher=Ibiblio |accessdate=5 April 2013}}\n</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==6 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=6 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|F 450||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The Type C2 ''[[Marinef\u00e4hrprahm]]'' was sunk on this date.<ref name=\"MFP landing craft, Germany\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_mfp.htm |title=MFP landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|F 519||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The Type B ''[[Marinef\u00e4hrprahm]]'' was heavily damaged by Allied fighter-bombers off [[Piombino]] and grounded. One crew was killed and four wounded. The wreck was then sunk in Piombino by another air attack either the 7th or the 19th.<ref name=\"MFP landing craft, Germany\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.historisches-marinearchiv.de/projekte/landungsfahrzeuge/marinefaehrprahm/ausgabe.php?where_value=556 |title=F 519 |publisher=www.historisches-marinearchiv.de |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Hsing Yun Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The transport ship struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[Yangtze-kiang]].<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|LCP(S) 9}}  \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The [[LCPL|landing craft personnel (small)]] was wrecked at [[Weymouth, England]].<ref name=\"LCP, LCPS, LCPL, LCPR Landing\">{{cite web |url= http://www.navypedia.org/ships/uk/brit_aws_lcp.htm |title=LCP, LCP(S), LCP(L), LCP(R) Landing Craft, Royal Navy |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Navalhistory.net\">{{cite web |url=http://www.naval-history.net/WW2BritishLossesbyDate3.htm |title=Royal Navy vessels lost at sea Jan. '44-Nov. '45 |publisher=Navalhistory.net |accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minesweeper|R-192||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[R boat|Type R-151 minesweeper]] was sunk in the [[Tyrrhenian Sea]] off [[Cecina, Tuscany]], Italy during a battle with [[Royal Navy]] [[motor torpedo boat]]s.<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref name=\"Warshipsww2.Eu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=764 |title=German coastal minesweeper Type R-218 |publisher=Warshipsww2.Eu |accessdate=3 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513030230/http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=764 |archive-date=13 May 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Ruth I||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy SC 156]]: The cargo ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] ({{coord|45|05|N|35|11|W}}) by {{GS|U-302||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of three of her 39 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{HMS|Chelmer|K221|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=Ruth>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/singleships/ruth.html |title=D/S Ruth |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=7 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|South America|1931|2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy SC 156]]: The [[tank ship|tanker]] was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|45|04|N|35|22|W}}) by {{GS|U-302||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). All 42 crew were rescued by {{SS|Goodwin||2}} ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}).<ref name=SA>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/singleships/southamerica.html |title=M/T South America |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=7 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-302||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|45|05|N|35|11|W}}) by {{HMS|Swale|K217|6}} ({{navy|UK}}) with the loss of all 51 crew.<ref name=U302>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u302.htm |title=U-302 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=15 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-455||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] struck a mine and sank in the [[Ligurian Sea]] off [[Portofino]], [[Province of Genoa|Genoa]], Italy with the loss of all 51 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Wesergau||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Norwegian Sea]] off [[Stad (peninsula)|Stad]], Norway by {{HNoMS|Ula|1943|2}} ({{navy|Norway}}).<ref name=\"Berg 1997 116\">{{Cite book|title=I skj\u00e6rg\u00e5rden og p\u00e5 havet \u2013 Marinens krig 8. april 1940 \u2013 8. mai 1945 |last=Berg |first=Ole F. |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1997 |publisher=Marinens krigsveteranforening |location=Oslo |isbn=82-993545-2-8 |page=116 |pages= |url= |language= Norwegian}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==7 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=7 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Asien||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[North Sea]] off [[Lista, Norway]] ({{coord|58|08|N|06|32|E}}) by {{HMS|Unshaken|P54|6}} ({{navy|UK}}). All her crew were saved by an escort ship.<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/3559.html |title=HMS Unshaken |publisher=uboat.net |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Jsub|I-2||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Type J1 submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Bismarck Sea]] {{convert|50|nmi|km}} west north west of [[New Hanover Island|New Hanover]], off [[Emirau Island]] ({{coord|02|17|S|149|14|E}}) by {{USS|Saufley|DD-465|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Lost with all 111 hands.<ref name=Saufley>{{cite DANFS | title = DD-465 | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/destroy/dd465txt.htm | accessdate = 21 January 2012 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Rion'' \n|flag={{flag|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=World War II: The barge struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[Black Sea]] ({{coord|42|11|N|41|38|E}}).<ref name=Rion>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3232.html |title=Rion |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-856||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type IX submarine|Type IX]] [[submarine]] was depth charged, shelled, rammed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] ({{coord|40|18|N|62|22|W}}) by {{USS|Champlin|DD-601|6}} and {{USS|Huse|DE-145|6}} (both {{navy|USA|1912}}) with the loss of 27 of her 55 crew.<ref name=BI>{{cite DANFS | title = Block Island | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/carriers/cve21.htm | accessdate = 12 January 2012 }}</ref><ref name=Champlin>{{cite DANFS | title = DD-601 | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/destroy/dd601txt.htm | accessdate = 30 December 2011 }}</ref><ref name=U856>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u856.htm |title=U-856 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=22 April 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==8 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=8 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese ammunition ship|Aratama Maru||2}} \n|flag={{Navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The ammunition ship was [[torpedo]]ed in the [[Pacific Ocean]] {{convert|7|nmi|km}} east of [[Guam]] ({{coord|13|16|N|145|11|E}}) by {{USS|Seahorse|SS-304|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Her cargo of gasoline exploded damaging {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Asakaze|1922|2}} ({{navy|Empire of Japan}}). She drifted on fire for three days before coming to rest on a reef, and sinking partially submerged in shallow water, in Talafofo Bay, Guam on 11 April. Four crewmen were killed. She eventually sank completely post-war after damage by many [[typhoon]]s over a number of years.<ref name=Seahorse>{{cite DANFS | title = Seahorse | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss304.txt | accessdate = 4 January 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Aratama_t.htm|title=Japanese Ammunition Ships |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=8 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Enco||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was sunk at [[Venice]] during an Allied air raid.<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Nebraska||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo ship]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[South 