Ocean]] {{convert|200|nmi|km}} east of [[New York City|New York]] ({{coord|40|05|N|69|40|W}}) by {{GS|U-550||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of ten gunners and fifteen of her 56 crew. Survivors abandoned ship and were rescued by {{USS|Joyce|DE-317|6}} and {{USS|Peterson|DE-152|6}} (both {{navy|USA|1912}}). Some of the shells fired by {{USS|Gandy|DE-764|6}}, ''Joyce'' and ''Peterson'' (all {{Navy|USA|1912}}) in sinking ''U-550'' hit ''Pan-Pennsylvania'' setting her on fire ({{coord|40|09|N|69|44|W}}). ''Pan-Pennsylvania'' was scuttled by bombing and sank on 18 April at {{coord|40|24|N|69|37|W}} by Allied aircraft.<ref name=Joyce>{{cite DANFS | title = Joyce | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/escorts/de317.txt | accessdate = 30 January 2012 }}</ref><ref name=PP>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3236.html |title=Pan Pennsylvania |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=6 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minesweeper|R-108||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[R boat|Type R-41 minesweeper]] was sunk in the [[North Sea]] off [[Terschelling]], [[Friesland]], Netherlands in a collision with {{ship|German minesweeper|R-229||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}).<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=762 |title=German coastal minesweeper Type R-41 |publisher=Warshipsww2.Eu |accessdate=2 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007024640/http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=762 |archive-date=7 October 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Shinyu Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo liner was torpedoed and sunk in the Philippine Sea by {{USS|Redfin|SS-272|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=Redfin>{{cite DANFS | title = Redfin | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss272.htm | accessdate = 4 January 2012 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Thomas G. Masaryk||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy UGS-37]]: The [[Liberty ship]] was torpedoed and damaged in the Mediterranean Sea {{convert|17|nmi|km}} off Derna ({{coord|32|51|N|23|00|E}}) by {{GS|U-407||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). All 70 crew abandoned ship and were rescued by {{HMS|La Malouine|K46|6}} ({{navy|UK}}). ''Thomas G. Masaryk'' was taken in tow by {{HMS|Captive|W148|6}} ({{navy|UK}}) and beached in [[Maneola Bay]]. She was shelled and sunk in order to extinguish the fire that had started when she was torpedoed. She was refloated on 28 August and towed by HMS ''Captive'' to [[Port Said]], Egypt but was declared a [[constructive total loss]].<ref name=LibT>{{cite web |url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/LibShipsT.html |title=Liberty Ships \u2013 T \u2013 U \u2013 V |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=6 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=TGM>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3234.html |title=Thomas G. Masaryk |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=22 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-550||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[File:U-550 crew abandons ship.jpg|thumb|''U-550'']]\nWorld War II: The [[German Type IX submarine|IXC/40]] [[submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d, shelled, rammed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|40|09|N|69|44|W}}) by {{USS|Gandy|DE-764|6}}, {{USS|Joyce|DE-317|6}} and {{USS|Peterson|DE-152|6}} (all {{Navy|USA|1912}}) with the loss of 44 of her 56 crew. Survivors were taken as [[prisoners of war]] by USS ''Joyce''.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Yamagata Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo liner]] was torpedoed and sunk in the Philippine Sea by {{USS|Redfin|SS-272|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). 28 passengers and 5 crewmen killed.<ref name=Redfin/> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==17 April==\n::For the sinking of the Japanese Navy tanker ''Iro'' on this date, see the entry for [[Li