hipboard)|lifeboat]], but only nine of them remained alive when the [[Steamship|steamer]] ''Ola'' ({{flag|Soviet Union}}) rescued them six days later. ''Pavlin Vinogradov''{{'}}s [[Sea captain|master]] did not survive.<ref name=alaskashipwrecksp>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-p/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (P)]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shipsnostalgia.com/guides/Soviet_Merchant_Marine_Losses_in_WW2_%28Black_Sea%2C_Caspian_and_Pacific%29  |title=Soviet Marine Losses in WWII (Pacific Ocean)|publisher=Shipnostalgia.com |accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minelayer|Roland||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The auxiliary [[minelayer]] struck a mine and sank in the Baltic Sea.<ref name=seekrieg194403>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wlb-stuttgart.de/seekrieg/44-03.htm |title=Seekrieg 1944, M\u00e4rz |accessdate=3 August 2015 |last=Rohwer |first=J\u00fcrgen |authorlink=J\u00fcrgen Rohwer |author2=Gerhard H\u00fcmmelchen |work=W\u00fcrttembergische Landesbibliothek Stuttgart |publisher= |language=German }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese submarine chaser|Shonan Maru No. 7||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[submarine chaser]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Strait of Malacca]] by {{HMS|Sea Rover|P218|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-311||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] south west of Iceland ({{coord|52|09|N|19|07|W}}) by {{HMCS|Matane|K444|6}} and {{HMCS|Swansea|K328|6}} (both {{navy|Canada|1911}}) with the loss of all 51 crew.<ref name=U311>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u311.html |title=U-311 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese tanker|Yamamizu Maru No. 3||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: Convoy SHISA-17: The [[tank ship|tanker]] was bombed and sunk in the South China Sea {{convert|2|nmi|km}} north east of Cape St. Jacques Lighthouse, French Indochina, by Consolidated B-24 Liberator aircraft of the 308th Bomb Group, United States Fourteenth Air Force. Eighteen crewmen were killed.<ref name=\"Japanese Transports\"/> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==23 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=23 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese destroyer|Amagiri|1930|2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The {{sclass-|Fubuki|destroyer}} was sunk in the [[Makassar Strait]] {{convert|50|nmi|km}} south of [[Balikpapan]] [[Borneo]] by a [[naval mine|mine]]. Thirteen crewmen were killed. Survivors were rescued by the [[heavy cruiser]] {{ship|Japanese cruiser|Aoba||2}} and the [[light cruiser]] {{ship|Japanese cruiser|\u014ci||2}} (both {{navy|Empire of Japan}}).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/amagir_t.htm |title=Long Lancers |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Daiju Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Seto Inland Sea]] by the [[submarine]] {{USS|Seadragon|SS-194|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=Seadragon>{{cite DANFS | title = Seadragon | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss194.txt | accessdate = 30 December 2011 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minesweeper|R 208||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[minesweeper]] struck a [[Naval mine|mine]] laid by an aircraft and sank in the [[Danube]].<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German motor torpedo boat|S 54||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[E-boat]] was badly damaged by a mine on this date. Subsequently decommissioned on 31 October 1944 and scrapped.<ref>[http://german-navy.de/kriegsmarine/ships/fastattack/schnellboot1939/ships.html Schnellboot 1939] german-navy.de accessed 28 November 2013</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Taiju Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo ship]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] south of [[Honshu]] by the [[submarine]] {{USS|Seadragon|SS-194|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=seekrieg194404/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German patrol ship|V 6109 Nordwind||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The ''Seeteufel''-class naval whaler/''[[Vorpostenboot]]'' was torpedoed and damaged by Soviet aircraft. She was taken under tow, but later that day was bombed and sunk off Vardo by Soviet aircraft. 17 of her 54 crew were killed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_esc_seeteufel.htm |title=Seeteufel Patrols, Germany|publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=Huan>{{cite book |title=La marine sovi\u00e9tique en guerre |first=Claude |last=Huan |publisher=Economica |year=1991 |isbn=978-2717819205}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==24 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=24 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|F 423||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The Type C ''[[Marinef\u00e4hrprahm]]'' was sunk on this date.<ref name=\"MFP landing craft, Germany\"/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|LST-407}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The [[Landing ship tank|Mk 2 landing ship tank]] was run aground off [[Naples, Italy]] and was not repaired. Returned to the United States Navy in May 1945.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/12294.html |title=HMS LST 407 of the Royal Navy |publisher=U Boat.net |accessdate=24 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|MTB 671}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The [[Fairmile D motor torpedo boat]] was