ia |accessdate=25 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German tug|O 22 S||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The [[tugboat|tug]] was sunk in an Allied air raid on [[Kiel]], [[Schleswig-Holstein]]. She was subsequently salvaged, repaired and returned to service.<ref name=Dunkirk>{{cite web |url=http://thamestugs.co.uk/DUNKIRK.php |title=Dunkirk |publisher=Thames Tugs |accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minesweeper|R-208||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[R boat|Type R-151 minesweeper]] was sunk in the [[Danube]] at [[Linz]], Austria by a [[naval mine|mine]].<ref name=\"Warshipsww2.Eu\"/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German torpedo boat|T27||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The torpedo boat was shelled and damaged in the [[English Channel]] in a battle with {{HMS|Ashanti|F51|6}}, {{HMS|Black Prince|81|6}} (both {{navy|UK}}), {{HMCS|Haida|G63|6}} and {{HMCS|Huron|G24|6}} (both {{navy|Canada|1911}}). She was beached at [[Morlaix]], [[Manche]], France on 27 April. ''T 27'' was further damaged in an air attack on 3 May and was torpedoed and sunk by {{ship|HMMTB|673}} on 7 May.<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German torpedo boat|T29||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The torpedo boat was shelled and sunk in the English Channel by {{HMCS|Haida|G63|6}} ({{navy|Canada|1911}}) with the loss of 62 of her 135 crew. Survivors were rescued by Kriegsmarine ''[[Vorpostenboot]]e''.<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German torpedo boat|TA23||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Ciclone|torpedo boat|2}} was damaged by a mine off [[Capraia]], Italy ({{coord|43|02|N|10|12|E}}). Scuttled by ''TA29'' ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) when attacked by Royal Navy motor torpedo boats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_dd_ta23.htm |title=TA23 Torpedo Boats (1942-1943/1943-1944) |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=25 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Tetsuyo Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] north west of [[Chichi-jima]] by {{USS|Guavina|SS-362|6}} ({{navy|United States|1912}}).<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German submarine chaser|UJ 206||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[submarine chaser]], a former {{sclass-|Gabbiano|corvette}}, was scuttled at [[Venice]], Italy after being damaged by Allied aircraft. Raised, repaired and returned to Italian service post-War.<ref name=\"WarshipsWW2\"/> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==26 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=26 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Colin||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Panama}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: [[Convoy SC 157]]: The cargo ship straggled behind the convoy due to steering gear defects. She was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] ({{coord|54|16|N|31|58|W}}) by {{GS|U-859||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of one of her 55 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{HMS|Affleck|K462|6}} and {{HMS|Bentley|K465|6}} (both {{navy|UK}}).<ref name=Colin>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3237.html |title=Colin |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=22 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Eugenio C.|1928|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was bombed and sunk by aircraft south of [[Bod\u00f8]], Norway.<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=1160588|shipname=Eugenio C. |accessdate=27 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Jsub|I-180||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Kaidai|submarine|2}} was [[depth charge]]d, [[hedgehog (weapon)|hedgehogged]] and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] south west of