17|54|N|38|05|W}}) by {{USS|Barber|DE-161|6}}, {{USS|Frost|DE-144|6}}, {{USS|Huse|DE-145|6}} and {{USS|Snowden|DE-246|6}} (all {{navy|USA|1912}}) with the loss of all 64 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German trawler|V 606 Fladengrund||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The ''[[Vorpostenboot]]'' was sunk in the [[Bay of Biscay]] south of [[Belle \u00cele]], [[Finist\u00e8re]], France in an Allied air raid.<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German trawler|V 1401 Deister||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The ''Vorpostenboot'' suffered a boiler explosion and sank in the North Sea off [[IJmuiden]], [[North Holland]], Netherlands.<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Wazan Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Kii Channel]] by {{USS|Sargo|SS-188|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=Sargo>{{cite DANFS | title = Sargo | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss188.txt | accessdate = 30 December 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?137603 |title=Wazan Maru cargo ship (1918\u20131944) |publisher=Wrecksite |accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Yoshida Maru No.1||2}} \n|flag={{army|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: Convoy TAKE No. 1: The transport was torpedoed and sunk in the [[South China Sea]] ({{coord|18|06|N|119|40|E}}) by {{USS|Jack|SS-259|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). 2,586 troops and 63 crewmen killed. 860 troops survived.<ref>{{cite web | title=Yoshida Maru No.1Passenger/cargo ship 1919\u20131944 | url=http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?137602 |publisher=Wrecksite.eu | accessdate=18 January 2013 }}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==27 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=27 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Akigawa Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The Standard Merchant Type 1K [[ore carrier]] was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] {{convert|150|nmi|km}} west of [[Saipan]] ({{coord|14|46|N|143|22|E}}) by the [[submarine]] {{USS|Seahorse|SS-304|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Two troops and an unknown number of others were killed.<ref name=Seahorse/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Axel|1878|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo ship]] was bombed and sunk by aircraft at the [[Deutsche Werke]] yard in [[Kiel]], [[Germany]].<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=1078412|shipname=Axel |accessdate=25 November 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Daisun'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[fishing trawler|trawler]] was shelled and sunk in the [[South China Sea]] by the [[submarine]] {{USS|Jack|SS-259|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=Jack>{{cite DANFS | title = Jack) | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss259.htm | accessdate = 4 January 2012 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Etamin|AK-93|6}} \n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Crater|cargo ship|2}} was torpedoed and damaged in [[Milne Bay]], [[New Guinea]], by Japanese aircraft. She consequently became a [[hulk (ship)|storage hulk]].\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Genbu Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: Convoy OKI-509: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] ({{coord|27|16|N|128|21|E}}) by the [[submarine]] {{USS|Halibut|SS-232|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Two troops and a crewman were killed.<ref name=Halibut/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese minelayer|Kamome||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: Convoy OKI-509: The {{sclass-|Tsubame|minelayer}} was torpedoed and sunk in the Pacific Ocean ({{coord|27|03|N|128|06|E}}) by the [[submarine]] {{USS|Halibut|SS-232|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=Halibut/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minesweeper|M 3668||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[minesweeper]], a  KFK-class [[naval drifter]], struck a mine and sank in the [[North Sea]] off [[Ostend]], [[West Flanders]], [[Belgium]].<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Soviet motor torpedo boat|TK-332||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The G-5-class [[motor torpedo boat]] was shelled and sunk by German and Romanian surface ships in the [[black sea]].<ref name=\"G-5 class motor torpedo boat, USSR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/russia/ru_cf_g5.htm |title=G-5 class motor torpedo boat, USSR |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Soviet Naval Losses Black Sea\">{{cite web |url=http://www.soviet-empire.com/ussr/viewtopic.php?f=149&t=53917&sid=0225559cd69b51f93f8b0cfbfab11342 |title=Soviet Naval Losses (Black Sea)|publisher=Sovietempire.com |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-803||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type IX submarine|Type IXC/40]] [[submarine]] struck a mine and sank in the [[Baltic Sea]] off [[Swinem\u00fcnde]], [[Province of Pomerania (1815-1945)|Pomerania]], with the loss of nine of her 44 crew. Salvaged in August 1944 and cannibalized for parts.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German submarine chaser|UJ 104||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The auxiliary submarine chaser was torpedoed by {{ship|Soviet motor torpedo boat|TK-344||2}} ({{navy|Soviet Union}}) in the Black Sea, losing her stern. 17 crew were killed. She was towed to Sebastopol and was scuttled there on 10 May.<ref name=\"Soviet Naval Losses Black Sea\">{{cite web |url=http://www.soviet-empire.com/ussr/viewtopic.php?f=149&t=53917&sid=0225559cd69b51f93f8b0cfbfab11342 |title=Soviet Naval Losses (Black Sea)|publisher=Sovietempire.com |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Die Kriegstransporter KT 1 - KT 62 der Deutschen Kriegsmarine: Konzept, Einsatz und Verbleib |first=Wilhelm |last=Donko |publisher=epubli |year=2013 |isbn=978-3-8442-5066-4}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German submarine chaser|UJ 6075 Clairvoyant||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[submarine chaser]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] ({{coord|43|01|N|05|58|E}}) off [[Toulon]], [[Var (department)|Var]], [[France]], by {{HMS|Untiring|P59|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194404/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=1898 |title=French patrol vessels type Trawlery |publisher=Warshipsww2.Eu |accessdate=29 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229212208/http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=1898 |archivedate=29 December 2014 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese cruiser|Y\u016bbari||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Y\u016bbari|cruiser|0}} [[light cruiser]] was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Pacific Ocean]] off [[Sonsorol Island]], southwest of [[Palau]] at ({{coord|5|20|N|132|16|E}}), by the [[submarine]] {{USS|Bluegill|SS-242|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). She sank the next day. Nineteen crewmen were killed. Survivors were rescued by the [[destroyer]] {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Y\u016bzuki||2}} ({{navy|Empire of Japan}}). }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==28 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=28 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|LST-507}} \n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: Convoy T-4: [[Exercise Tiger|Battle of Lyme Bay]]: The [[landing ship tank]] was torpedoed and sunk in [[Lyme Bay]] ({{coord|50|28|N|02|51|W}}) by {{ship|German torpedo boat|S 100||2}}, {{ship|German torpedo boat|S 130||2}}, {{ship|German torpedo boat|S 136||2}}, {{ship|German torpedo boat|S 138||2}}. {{ship|German torpedo boat|S 140||2}}, {{ship|German tor