|1936}} was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[English Channel]] off [[Saint-Brieuc]], [[C\u00f4tes-du-Nord]], France by {{ship|German torpedo boat|T24||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 124 of her 219 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Jsub|I-183||2}}<!--misnamed in source, see class article--> \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Kaidai|submarine|2}} was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] {{convert|30|nmi|km}} south of Cape Ashizuri, Japan ({{coord|32|07|N|133|03|E}}) by {{USS|Pogy|SS-266|6}} ({{navy|United States|1912}}).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/I-183_t.htm |title=Imperial Submarines |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=28 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=[[Motor Torpedo Boat PT-346|USS ''PT-346'']]\n|flag={{navy|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass2-|ELCO 80'|PT boat}} was accidentally sunk in the [[Bismarck Sea]] off Cape Lambert, [[New Britain Island]] ({{coord|04|13|S|151|27|E}}) by [[Vought F4U Corsair]], [[Grumman F6F Hellcat]], [[Douglas SBD Dauntless]], and [[Grumman TBF Avenger]] aircraft of the [[United States Navy]]. Nine crew were killed. Survivors were rescued by [[Consolidated PBY Catalina]] aircraft of the United States Navy.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/10273.html |title=PT 346 of the US Navy |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|PT-347}} \n|flag={{navy|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass2-|ELCO 80'|PT boat}} was sunk in the Bismarck Sea off Cape Lambert, [[New Britain Island]] ({{coord|04|13|S|151|27|E}}) by Vought F4U Corsair, Grumman F6F Hellcat, Douglas SBD Dauntless and Grumman TBF Avenger aircraft of the United States Navy. Survivors were rescued by Consolidated PBY Catalina aircraft of the United States Navy.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/10274.html |title=PT 347 of the US Navy |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Pulo Salanama||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[coastal trading vessel|coaster]] was shelled and sunk in the [[Malacca Strait]] ({{coord|03|19|N|99|44|E}}) by {{HMS|Tantalus|P318|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/3517.html |title=HMS Tantulus of the Royal Navy |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German torpedo boat|S 54||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The ''[[Schnellboot]]'' struck a mine and was damaged in the [[Aegean Sea]]. She was taken in to [[Salonika]], Greece but was not repaired.<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Song Giang Go||2}} \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[South China Sea]] off Cape Varella, [[French Indochina]] by {{USS|Flasher|SS-249|6}} ({{navy|United States|1912}}).<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German torpedo boat|T-27||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass2-|Elbing|torpedo boat|2}} was sunk with gunfire at [[Brignogan-Plages]], [[Finist\u00e8re]], France.<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=6116673|shipname=T-27 |accessdate=21 July 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|French aviso|Tahure||2}} \n|flag={{flagicon|France}} [[Vichy France|Vichy French Navy]]\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Arras|aviso}} was torpedoed and sunk in the South China Sea off the Hon Doi Islands, Cape Varella, French Indochina ({{coord|13|02|N|109|28|E}}) by {{USS|Flasher|SS-249|6}} ({{navy|United States|1912}}).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/6174.html |title=Fr Tahure of the French Navy |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/CD-138_t.htm|title=Combinedfleet CD-138 |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=2 January 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Takegawa Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: Convoy TAMA-17: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Pacific Ocean ({{coord|19|20|N|118|50|E}}) by {{USS|Bang|SS-385|6}} ({{navy|United States|1912}}). Seven crewmen were killed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Sanluis_t.htm|title=Japanese Oilers |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-421||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was bombed and sunk at [[Toulon]], [[Var (department)|Var]] France during an American air raid.<ref name=U421>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u421.htm |title=U-421 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==30 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=30 April 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese auxiliary submarine chaser|CHa-38||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The [[No.1-class auxiliary submarine chaser|''CHa-1''-class]] auxiliary [[submarine chaser]] was sunk at [[Chuuk Atoll|Truk]] by American aircraft.<ref name=\"1-Go auxiliary submarine chasers\"/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Nittatsu Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: Convoy TAMA-17: The cargo ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] ({{coord|19|22|N|118|45|E}}) by {{USS|Bang|SS-385|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Four crewmen were killed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Belgium_t.htm|title=Japanese Army Auxiliary Tankers |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Jsub|Ro-45||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Kaich\u016b type submarine|''Kaich\u016b'' type submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the Pacific Ocean {{convert|40|nmi|km}} south of [[Chuuk Atoll|Truk]] ({{coord|06|13|N|151|19|E}}) by {{USS|Macdonough|DD-351|6}} and {{USS|Stephen Potter|DD-538|6}} (both {{navy|United States|1912}}). She was lost with all 74 crew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/RO-45.htm |title=RO-45 |publisher=www.combinedfleet.com |accessdate=20 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|William S. Thayer||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy RA 59]]: The [[Liberty ship]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Barents Sea]] off [[Bear Island (Norway)|Bear Island]], Norway by {{GS|U-307||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 43 of the 234 people on board. Survivors were rescued by {{SS|Robert Eden||2}} ({{flag|United States|1912}} and {{HMS|Whitehall|D94|6}} ({{navy|UK}}), which scuttled the still-floating stern section of the ship.<ref name=WST>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3238.html |title=William S. Thayer |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=15 March 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==Unknown date==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=Unknown date 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|F 394||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The Type C ''[[Marinef\u00e4hrprahm]]'' was sunk in the [[Black Sea]] by [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] aircraft between 8 and 16 April.<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|F 395||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The Type C ''Marinef\u00e4hrprahm'' was sunk in the Black Sea by Soviet aircraft between 8 and 16 April.<ref name=seekrieg194404/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|F 608||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The Type C2 ''[[Marinef\u00e4hrprahm]]'' was sunk sometime in April.<ref name=\"MFP landing craft, Germany\"/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship= {{HMS|LCM 1313}}, {{HMS|LCM 1314}}, {{HMS|LCM 1373}} and 